The Rust DrawableManager (drawable_manager.rs:331-337) has a hardcoded expiry logic for "very old drawables":
```rust
let frames_alive = self.current_frame.saturating_sub(entry.creation_frame);
if frames_alive > 36000 {  // ~10 minutes at 60 FPS
    return Some(id);
}
```

This logic does NOT exist in C++. C++ drawable lifecycle is entirely driven by GameLogic object lifecycle - when an object is destroyed, its drawable is removed. This Rust-only expiry code could prematurely destroy legitimate drawables that happen to exist longer than ~10 minutes (e.g., buildings, static props, persistent effects).

This appears to be a debugging safeguard that was left in production code. It should be removed or made configurable with a much higher threshold.

